1
01:00:00,166 --> 01:00:02,333
<b>What if the biggest threat to your bank</b>

2
01:00:02,333 --> 01:00:04,533
<b>account is not what you think it is?</b>

3
01:00:05,066 --> 01:00:05,900
<b>It's not inflation,</b>

4
01:00:06,300 --> 01:00:07,733
<b>it's not the stock market.</b>

5
01:00:08,433 --> 01:00:11,099
<b>It's a 200 years old lie.</b>

6
01:00:11,766 --> 01:00:13,366
<b>A single stubborn myth</b>

7
01:00:13,366 --> 01:00:15,199
<b>from the 19th century</b>

8
01:00:15,766 --> 01:00:17,333
<b>that political leaders</b>

9
01:00:17,333 --> 01:00:18,933
<b>are still using today</b>

10
01:00:19,366 --> 01:00:21,533
<b>to sell you on trade wars.</b>

11
01:00:21,933 --> 01:00:23,366
<b>And no, this isn't</b>

12
01:00:23,366 --> 01:00:24,699
<b>some conspiracy theory.</b>

13
01:00:25,333 --> 01:00:25,666
<b>It's a</b>

14
01:00:25,666 --> 01:00:27,633
<b>well-documented political playbook.</b>

15
01:00:28,800 --> 01:00:30,633
<b>Today we're pulling back the curtains to</b>

16
01:00:30,633 --> 01:00:32,466
<b>show you how this one idea</b>

17
01:00:32,666 --> 01:00:34,066
<b>is still justifying</b>

18
01:00:34,066 --> 01:00:36,033
<b>destructive economic policies</b>

19
01:00:36,400 --> 01:00:37,866
<b>that hurt you, your</b>

20
01:00:37,866 --> 01:00:39,900
<b>country and the global economy.</b>

21
01:00:40,400 --> 01:00:41,166
<b>It seems like everywhere</b>

22
01:00:41,166 --> 01:00:43,466
<b>you look, walls are going up.</b>

23
01:00:43,866 --> 01:00:45,199
<b>We are living in an age</b>

24
01:00:45,199 --> 01:00:46,833
<b>of escalating trade wars.</b>

25
01:00:47,533 --> 01:00:49,099
<b>Just in the last few years</b>

26
01:00:49,099 --> 01:00:51,066
<b>we've seen massive new taxes</b>

27
01:00:51,266 --> 01:00:54,133
<b>called tariffs slapped on goods worth</b>

28
01:00:54,133 --> 01:00:55,500
<b>billions of dollars.</b>

29
01:00:56,233 --> 01:00:59,266
<b>Everything from cars and steel to washing</b>

30
01:00:59,266 --> 01:01:01,166
<b>machines and solar panels.</b>

31
01:01:02,033 --> 01:01:03,866
<b>The United States and China are locked</b>

32
01:01:03,866 --> 01:01:05,833
<b>into an economic slugfest</b>

33
01:01:06,033 --> 01:01:07,233
<b>that has sent tremors</b>

34
01:01:07,233 --> 01:01:08,699
<b>around the entire globe.</b>

35
01:01:09,266 --> 01:01:11,233
<b>And the sales pitch is always the same.</b>

36
01:01:11,633 --> 01:01:13,866
<b>We're told it's about getting tough,</b>

37
01:01:14,133 --> 01:01:16,333
<b>protecting our jobs and</b>

38
01:01:16,333 --> 01:01:17,900
<b>putting America first.</b>

39
01:01:18,233 --> 01:01:20,433
<b>Politicians stand on podiums</b>

40
01:01:20,433 --> 01:01:21,800
<b>and sell us a simple story.</b>

41
01:01:22,066 --> 01:01:23,300
<b>To be strong, a nation</b>

42
01:01:23,300 --> 01:01:24,633
<b>has to be self-sufficient.</b>

43
01:01:25,099 --> 01:01:27,599
<b>They frame global trade as a</b>

44
01:01:27,599 --> 01:01:29,033
<b>winner-take-all brawl,</b>

45
01:01:29,533 --> 01:01:32,166
<b>where if one country is losing it means</b>

46
01:01:32,166 --> 01:01:33,500
<b>another one is winning.</b>

47
01:01:34,066 --> 01:01:36,266
<b>They wrap these policies in the flag,</b>

48
01:01:36,733 --> 01:01:39,633
<b>using patriotism and national security as</b>

49
01:01:39,633 --> 01:01:41,433
<b>an excuse for these tariffs.</b>

50
01:01:41,933 --> 01:01:43,433
<b>But let's be clear about</b>

51
01:01:43,433 --> 01:01:44,833
<b>who pays these tariffs.</b>

52
01:01:45,433 --> 01:01:46,866
<b>You do. The consumer.</b>

53
01:01:47,300 --> 01:01:48,333
<b>And it works because</b>

54
01:01:48,333 --> 01:01:49,766
<b>it's a powerful narrative.</b>

55
01:01:50,300 --> 01:01:51,633
<b>It plays on our real</b>

56
01:01:51,633 --> 01:01:53,033
<b>anxieties about the economy</b>

57
01:01:53,433 --> 01:01:56,000
<b>and our desire for national pride.</b>

58
01:01:56,466 --> 01:01:59,466
<b>But this story, this excuse for building</b>

59
01:01:59,466 --> 01:02:01,500
<b>walls, is not something new.</b>

60
01:02:01,966 --> 01:02:05,166
<b>It's a carefully crafted myth with roots</b>

61
01:02:05,166 --> 01:02:06,900
<b>stretching back to centuries.</b>

62
01:02:07,466 --> 01:02:10,500
<b>And to see why it's so dangerous now,</b>

63
01:02:10,500 --> 01:02:11,633
<b>we have to understand</b>

64
01:02:11,633 --> 01:02:12,833
<b>where it all started.</b>

65
01:02:13,366 --> 01:02:16,699
<b>Let's rewind to the 19th century, a time</b>

66
01:02:16,699 --> 01:02:18,066
<b>of explosive change.</b>

67
01:02:18,500 --> 01:02:19,833
<b>The Industrial Revolution</b>

68
01:02:19,833 --> 01:02:21,400
<b>was tearing through the world,</b>

69
01:02:21,866 --> 01:02:23,233
<b>but not evenly.</b>

70
01:02:23,966 --> 01:02:24,833
<b>Great Britain was the</b>

71
01:02:24,833 --> 01:02:27,133
<b>undisputed factory of the world.</b>

72
01:02:27,633 --> 01:02:29,866
<b>While other countries like a young United</b>

73
01:02:29,866 --> 01:02:32,533
<b>States and a newly formed Germany</b>

74
01:02:32,800 --> 01:02:34,366
<b>were struggling to keep up.</b>

75
01:02:34,666 --> 01:02:37,533
<b>For both of these two rising nations,</b>

76
01:02:37,866 --> 01:02:39,166
<b>Great Britain's power was</b>

77
01:02:39,166 --> 01:02:41,400
<b>both impressive and threatening.</b>

78
01:02:41,966 --> 01:02:44,533
<b>Enter Friedrich List, a German economist.</b>

79
01:02:45,133 --> 01:02:48,266
<b>List looked at the popular ideas of free</b>

80
01:02:48,266 --> 01:02:50,433
<b>trade thinkers like Adam Smith</b>

81
01:02:50,800 --> 01:02:52,566
<b>and said, "Hold on a second."</b>

82
01:02:52,900 --> 01:02:55,000
<b>He argued that free trade</b>

83
01:02:55,000 --> 01:02:56,633
<b>was a great deal for Britain</b>

84
01:02:56,766 --> 01:02:58,933
<b>because they were already the champions.</b>

85
01:02:59,533 --> 01:03:02,533
<b>For everyone else, he saw it as a trap.</b>

86
01:03:02,733 --> 01:03:06,066
<b>A one-way ticket to become Britain's</b>

87
01:03:06,066 --> 01:03:09,533
<b>permanent economic junior varsity team.</b>

88
01:03:09,800 --> 01:03:11,866
<b>So List cooked up a</b>

89
01:03:11,866 --> 01:03:13,566
<b>powerful counter-argument.</b>

90
01:03:14,233 --> 01:03:16,833
<b>One that would become the blueprint for</b>

91
01:03:16,833 --> 01:03:17,933
<b>economic nationalism.</b>

92
01:03:18,800 --> 01:03:20,166
<b>He said that for a nation</b>

93
01:03:20,166 --> 01:03:22,066
<b>to build its own industries,</b>

94
01:03:22,466 --> 01:03:25,266
<b>it had to protect its infant industries.</b>

95
01:03:25,733 --> 01:03:26,633
<b>His solution?</b>

96
01:03:27,300 --> 01:03:27,933
<b>Protective tariffs.</b>

97
01:03:28,366 --> 01:03:31,466
<b>By taxing imported goods, a country makes</b>

98
01:03:31,466 --> 01:03:33,033
<b>foreign goods more expensive.</b>

99
01:03:33,266 --> 01:03:36,633
<b>This gives its own companies the time</b>

100
01:03:36,633 --> 01:03:39,233
<b>they need to grow, to innovate,</b>

101
01:03:39,566 --> 01:03:42,333
<b>without being steamrolled by cheaper,</b>

102
01:03:42,333 --> 01:03:43,633
<b>more powerful competitors.</b>

103
01:03:44,166 --> 01:03:47,266
<b>He even called it an Ertigumstol,</b>

104
01:03:47,300 --> 01:03:48,866
<b>a temporary investment</b>

105
01:03:48,866 --> 01:03:50,433
<b>in the country's future.</b>

106
01:03:50,866 --> 01:03:52,699
<b>Now, this wasn't a totally new idea.</b>

107
01:03:53,033 --> 01:03:54,866
<b>In the US, figures like Alexander</b>

108
01:03:54,866 --> 01:03:56,866
<b>Hamilton had argued for</b>

109
01:03:56,866 --> 01:03:59,300
<b>similar measures decades earlier.</b>

110
01:03:59,566 --> 01:04:02,166
<b>But Hamilton proposed moderate tariffs</b>

111
01:04:02,166 --> 01:04:03,966
<b>paired with subsidies,</b>

112
01:04:04,333 --> 01:04:07,666
<b>largely for revenue and to give fledgling</b>

113
01:04:07,666 --> 01:04:09,900
<b>American industries a fair shot.</b>

114
01:04:10,400 --> 01:04:11,633
<b>List was the one who</b>

115
01:04:11,633 --> 01:04:13,866
<b>packaged it, popularized it,</b>

116
01:04:14,000 --> 01:04:15,599
<b>and gave it the harder nationalist</b>

117
01:04:15,599 --> 01:04:18,199
<b>framing that swept across the world.</b>

118
01:04:18,900 --> 01:04:19,933
<b>And on the surface,</b>

119
01:04:19,933 --> 01:04:21,199
<b>it sounds pretty smart.</b>

120
01:04:21,633 --> 01:04:23,800
<b>What nation doesn't want to be strong?</b>

121
01:04:24,300 --> 01:04:26,866
<b>And just like that, the myth was born.</b>

122
01:04:27,266 --> 01:04:28,400
<b>The belief that trade</b>

123
01:04:28,400 --> 01:04:30,633
<b>barriers are the road to wealth,</b>

124
01:04:31,033 --> 01:04:31,933
<b>and that economic</b>

125
01:04:31,933 --> 01:04:34,133
<b>isolation is a sign of strength.</b>

126
01:04:34,133 --> 01:04:36,400
<b>It was a story of national destiny.</b>

127
01:04:36,733 --> 01:04:38,966
<b>The only problem is that once you start</b>

128
01:04:38,966 --> 01:04:39,933
<b>looking at the facts,</b>

129
01:04:39,933 --> 01:04:41,800
<b>it starts falling apart.</b>

130
01:04:42,166 --> 01:04:44,500
<b>The core promise of this 200-year-old</b>

131
01:04:44,500 --> 01:04:47,633
<b>myth is that protectionism creates jobs</b>

132
01:04:47,633 --> 01:04:49,266
<b>and makes countries rich.</b>

133
01:04:49,566 --> 01:04:51,866
<b>But history tells a much darker story.</b>

134
01:04:52,633 --> 01:04:55,466
<b>The most infamous cautionary tale is that</b>

135
01:04:55,466 --> 01:04:58,666
<b>of the Smooth Haley Tariff Act</b>

136
01:04:58,666 --> 01:05:01,166
<b>of 1930 in the United States.</b>

137
01:05:02,033 --> 01:05:04,166
<b>Passed right after the Great Depression</b>

138
01:05:04,166 --> 01:05:06,533
<b>was sinking its teeth into the world,</b>

139
01:05:06,800 --> 01:05:09,433
<b>the act jacked up tariffs on</b>

140
01:05:09,433 --> 01:05:11,800
<b>over 20,000 imported goods.</b>

141
01:05:12,366 --> 01:05:14,133
<b>The goal, they said, was to shield</b>

142
01:05:14,133 --> 01:05:16,500
<b>American farmers and businesses from</b>

143
01:05:16,500 --> 01:05:17,566
<b>foreign competition.</b>

144
01:05:18,033 --> 01:05:20,033
<b>The result was an absolute catastrophe,</b>

145
01:05:20,266 --> 01:05:21,699
<b>while not the sole cause</b>

146
01:05:21,699 --> 01:05:22,866
<b>of the Great Depression,</b>

147
01:05:23,366 --> 01:05:25,433
<b>which was driven by factors like bank</b>

148
01:05:25,433 --> 01:05:27,833
<b>failures and monetary contraction.</b>

149
01:05:28,333 --> 01:05:30,666
<b>The Smooth Haley Tariff is wildly blamed</b>

150
01:05:30,666 --> 01:05:32,500
<b>for drastically worsening it.</b>

151
01:05:33,166 --> 01:05:35,766
<b>Instead of protecting the US economy, the</b>

152
01:05:35,766 --> 01:05:37,266
<b>Smooth Haley Act kicked</b>

153
01:05:37,266 --> 01:05:38,866
<b>off a global trade war.</b>

154
01:05:39,333 --> 01:05:41,699
<b>Other countries almost immediately hit</b>

155
01:05:41,699 --> 01:05:44,400
<b>back with their own retaliatory tariffs.</b>

156
01:05:45,233 --> 01:05:47,533
<b>Global trade didn't just slow down.</b>

157
01:05:47,766 --> 01:05:51,000
<b>It collapsed, falling by 65% and pushing</b>

158
01:05:51,000 --> 01:05:53,266
<b>the world deeper into economic misery.</b>

159
01:05:53,733 --> 01:05:54,866
<b>This didn't save</b>

160
01:05:54,866 --> 01:05:57,066
<b>jobs, it evaporated them.</b>

161
01:05:57,566 --> 01:05:59,099
<b>Now, fast forward to</b>

162
01:05:59,099 --> 01:06:00,366
<b>the end of World War II.</b>

163
01:06:00,866 --> 01:06:03,666
<b>The world's leaders, having learned their</b>

164
01:06:03,666 --> 01:06:05,099
<b>lesson from Smooth Haley,</b>

165
01:06:05,566 --> 01:06:07,099
<b>tried the exact opposite.</b>

166
01:06:07,599 --> 01:06:10,466
<b>They built a new system designed to lower</b>

167
01:06:10,466 --> 01:06:13,166
<b>trade barriers, creating institutions</b>

168
01:06:13,166 --> 01:06:15,300
<b>like the World Trade Organization.</b>

169
01:06:16,300 --> 01:06:19,166
<b>This shift towards global cooperation</b>

170
01:06:19,166 --> 01:06:20,800
<b>unleashed an era of</b>

171
01:06:20,800 --> 01:06:22,933
<b>unprecedented growth and prosperity,</b>

172
01:06:23,400 --> 01:06:26,166
<b>lifting about 1 billion people out of</b>

173
01:06:26,166 --> 01:06:29,033
<b>extreme poverty since 1990 alone.</b>

174
01:06:29,400 --> 01:06:31,833
<b>And guess what? Our recent experiments</b>

175
01:06:31,833 --> 01:06:34,566
<b>with trade wars only confirm</b>

176
01:06:34,566 --> 01:06:36,533
<b>what history has thought of.</b>

177
01:06:36,966 --> 01:06:40,066
<b>Study after study on recent trade wars</b>

178
01:06:40,066 --> 01:06:42,633
<b>showed that the country imposing the</b>

179
01:06:42,633 --> 01:06:44,366
<b>tariff pays the price.</b>

180
01:06:44,933 --> 01:06:47,366
<b>One analysis from the Peterson Institute</b>

181
01:06:47,366 --> 01:06:48,933
<b>for International Economics</b>

182
01:06:48,933 --> 01:06:51,966
<b>found that the steel tariffs</b>

183
01:06:52,066 --> 01:06:55,900
<b>costs the US consumers around $900,000</b>

184
01:06:55,900 --> 01:06:58,099
<b>for every job they created.</b>

185
01:06:58,333 --> 01:07:00,300
<b>A Yale study found that the recent</b>

186
01:07:00,300 --> 01:07:03,000
<b>tariffs cost the average American</b>

187
01:07:03,000 --> 01:07:04,699
<b>household thousands of</b>

188
01:07:04,699 --> 01:07:06,866
<b>dollars in higher prices.</b>

189
01:07:07,433 --> 01:07:08,166
<b>Think about your</b>

190
01:07:08,166 --> 01:07:10,500
<b>phone, your shoes, your car.</b>

191
01:07:11,166 --> 01:07:12,066
<b>Tariffs make all of</b>

192
01:07:12,066 --> 01:07:13,466
<b>these things more expensive.</b>

193
01:07:13,900 --> 01:07:14,866
<b>But what about jobs?</b>

194
01:07:15,533 --> 01:07:17,066
<b>The promise of bringing back</b>

195
01:07:17,066 --> 01:07:19,633
<b>manufacturing almost never plays out.</b>

196
01:07:19,966 --> 01:07:20,866
<b>A few protected</b>

197
01:07:20,866 --> 01:07:23,566
<b>industries might see tiny gains,</b>

198
01:07:24,033 --> 01:07:27,000
<b>but those are almost always wiped out by</b>

199
01:07:27,000 --> 01:07:28,900
<b>job losses everywhere else.</b>

200
01:07:29,633 --> 01:07:32,033
<b>Companies that need imported parts get</b>

201
01:07:32,033 --> 01:07:33,666
<b>slammed by higher costs.</b>

202
01:07:34,766 --> 01:07:37,266
<b>Farmers get locked out of foreign markets</b>

203
01:07:37,266 --> 01:07:39,233
<b>when other countries retaliate.</b>

204
01:07:39,633 --> 01:07:42,066
<b>The net result is almost always fewer</b>

205
01:07:42,066 --> 01:07:44,000
<b>jobs and a weaker economy.</b>

206
01:07:44,433 --> 01:07:47,033
<b>The myth that protectionism is some kind</b>

207
01:07:47,033 --> 01:07:48,466
<b>of magic wand for the</b>

208
01:07:48,466 --> 01:07:50,566
<b>economy is just that.</b>

209
01:07:51,133 --> 01:07:51,733
<b>A myth.</b>

210
01:07:52,366 --> 01:07:54,900
<b>It sounds great on a teleprompter, but it</b>

211
01:07:54,900 --> 01:07:57,166
<b>crumbles under the weight of reality.</b>

212
01:07:57,933 --> 01:07:59,866
<b>So if the evidence is so overwhelmingly</b>

213
01:07:59,866 --> 01:08:03,366
<b>clear, why does this 200-year-old idea</b>

214
01:08:03,366 --> 01:08:05,966
<b>still have such a death grip on politics?</b>

215
01:08:06,599 --> 01:08:08,800
<b>The answer is brutally simple.</b>

216
01:08:09,566 --> 01:08:10,933
<b>It works.</b>

217
01:08:12,133 --> 01:08:13,233
<b>Politically, that is.</b>

218
01:08:13,566 --> 01:08:15,233
<b>In times of economic anxiety</b>

219
01:08:15,233 --> 01:08:17,366
<b>when people feel left behind,</b>

220
01:08:17,899 --> 01:08:21,000
<b>the siren song of economic nationalism is</b>

221
01:08:21,000 --> 01:08:23,766
<b>an extremely effective way to gain votes.</b>

222
01:08:24,399 --> 01:08:25,633
<b>It offers a simple</b>

223
01:08:25,633 --> 01:08:27,433
<b>story with a simple villain.</b>

224
01:08:27,833 --> 01:08:29,666
<b>It is all the fault of</b>

225
01:08:29,666 --> 01:08:31,733
<b>unfair foreign competition.</b>

226
01:08:32,233 --> 01:08:33,866
<b>And it offers a simple solution.</b>

227
01:08:34,533 --> 01:08:36,533
<b>Build the wall, tax the goods.</b>

228
01:08:37,033 --> 01:08:39,533
<b>It lets a leader look like the protector</b>

229
01:08:39,533 --> 01:08:41,866
<b>of the little guy, fighting against</b>

230
01:08:41,866 --> 01:08:43,666
<b>shadowy outside forces.</b>

231
01:08:44,399 --> 01:08:46,233
<b>This story works because it</b>

232
01:08:46,233 --> 01:08:48,100
<b>taps into real frustrations.</b>

233
01:08:48,866 --> 01:08:51,100
<b>But instead of tackling the complex</b>

234
01:08:51,100 --> 01:08:52,699
<b>domestic problems that are</b>

235
01:08:52,699 --> 01:08:54,966
<b>often the real source of the pain,</b>

236
01:08:55,000 --> 01:08:57,633
<b>it redirects all that anger towards</b>

237
01:08:57,633 --> 01:08:59,233
<b>people in other countries.</b>

238
01:08:59,733 --> 01:09:00,366
<b>It's the oldest</b>

239
01:09:00,366 --> 01:09:02,033
<b>political trick in the book.</b>

240
01:09:02,633 --> 01:09:03,266
<b>Misdirection.</b>

241
01:09:04,166 --> 01:09:05,733
<b>We see this playbook</b>

242
01:09:05,733 --> 01:09:07,566
<b>running on the loop today.</b>

243
01:09:08,166 --> 01:09:11,966
<b>The rhetoric behind Brexit, the US-China</b>

244
01:09:11,966 --> 01:09:14,466
<b>trade war, and the rise of nationalist</b>

245
01:09:14,466 --> 01:09:17,733
<b>parties across the globe all drink from</b>

246
01:09:17,733 --> 01:09:19,166
<b>the same poisoned well.</b>

247
01:09:19,633 --> 01:09:23,166
<b>They use these old myths to sell policies</b>

248
01:09:23,166 --> 01:09:26,233
<b>that the evidence says that will hurt the</b>

249
01:09:26,233 --> 01:09:28,000
<b>people that they claim to be protecting.</b>

250
01:09:28,566 --> 01:09:31,033
<b>They sell a fantasy of strength through</b>

251
01:09:31,033 --> 01:09:34,166
<b>isolation, at the exact same moment that</b>

252
01:09:34,166 --> 01:09:35,466
<b>the world has become more</b>

253
01:09:35,466 --> 01:09:36,833
<b>interconnected than ever.</b>

254
01:09:37,433 --> 01:09:38,233
<b>Tearing up those</b>

255
01:09:38,233 --> 01:09:40,266
<b>connections doesn't make you strong.</b>

256
01:09:40,500 --> 01:09:43,300
<b>It injects chaos into the system, raises</b>

257
01:09:43,300 --> 01:09:46,000
<b>costs for everyone, and makes the world a</b>

258
01:09:46,000 --> 01:09:47,066
<b>more dangerous place.</b>

259
01:09:47,699 --> 01:09:50,433
<b>So how do you fight a 200-year-old lie?</b>

260
01:09:51,033 --> 01:09:52,833
<b>With the one thing that manipulative</b>

261
01:09:52,833 --> 01:09:54,899
<b>stories can't stand.</b>

262
01:09:55,466 --> 01:09:56,266
<b>The truth.</b>

263
01:09:56,766 --> 01:09:58,966
<b>The solution is to understand the gap</b>

264
01:09:58,966 --> 01:10:00,600
<b>between the political sales</b>

265
01:10:00,600 --> 01:10:02,966
<b>pitch and the economic reality.</b>

266
01:10:03,666 --> 01:10:05,733
<b>The reality is that trade</b>

267
01:10:05,733 --> 01:10:07,366
<b>isn't a battle to the death.</b>

268
01:10:07,833 --> 01:10:10,633
<b>Global cooperation has fueled innovation</b>

269
01:10:10,633 --> 01:10:13,166
<b>and has lifted about a billion people out</b>

270
01:10:13,166 --> 01:10:14,866
<b>of poverty since 1990.</b>

271
01:10:15,733 --> 01:10:18,166
<b>The reality is that tariffs are just</b>

272
01:10:18,166 --> 01:10:21,033
<b>taxes paid by the country's own</b>

273
01:10:21,033 --> 01:10:22,199
<b>businesses and</b>

274
01:10:22,199 --> 01:10:24,933
<b>consumers, not by foreign nations.</b>

275
01:10:25,533 --> 01:10:27,866
<b>And the reality is that the policies sold</b>

276
01:10:27,866 --> 01:10:30,566
<b>under economic patriotism have a long and</b>

277
01:10:30,566 --> 01:10:32,433
<b>ugly track record of leading to</b>

278
01:10:32,433 --> 01:10:33,800
<b>instability, higher</b>

279
01:10:33,800 --> 01:10:35,733
<b>prices, and lost jobs.</b>

280
01:10:36,233 --> 01:10:37,966
<b>When we understand the real history and</b>

281
01:10:37,966 --> 01:10:39,266
<b>the real economics, we</b>

282
01:10:39,266 --> 01:10:40,966
<b>take away the myths' power.</b>

283
01:10:41,500 --> 01:10:43,933
<b>We can see past the patriotic slogans and</b>

284
01:10:43,933 --> 01:10:45,066
<b>see the policies for</b>

285
01:10:45,066 --> 01:10:46,233
<b>what they really are.</b>

286
01:10:46,633 --> 01:10:49,266
<b>A political game that gambles with our</b>

287
01:10:49,266 --> 01:10:50,466
<b>financial well-being.</b>

288
01:10:50,833 --> 01:10:53,600
<b>We can demand policies based on evidence,</b>

289
01:10:53,933 --> 01:10:56,233
<b>not a tired, destructive myth.</b>

290
01:10:56,933 --> 01:10:58,066
<b>History has screamed a</b>

291
01:10:58,066 --> 01:11:00,266
<b>lesson to us time and again.</b>

292
01:11:00,833 --> 01:11:03,399
<b>Building walls leads to decay. Building</b>

293
01:11:03,399 --> 01:11:05,533
<b>bridges leads to prosperity.</b>

294
01:11:06,166 --> 01:11:08,899
<b>The choice is ours, but we have to make</b>

295
01:11:08,899 --> 01:11:10,566
<b>it with our eyes open.</b>

296
01:11:11,100 --> 01:11:13,033
<b>If this breakdown made sense</b>

297
01:11:13,033 --> 01:11:14,866
<b>to you, then please share it.</b>

298
01:11:15,199 --> 01:11:17,800
<b>The best way to disarm a harmful myth is</b>

299
01:11:17,800 --> 01:11:18,899
<b>to spread the truth.</b>

